## When to Use This Pattern vs. Permanent Fork

| Condition | Pattern |
|-----------|---------|
| Upstream last commit ≤18 months | Temporary fork → PR |
| Upstream last commit >18 months, issues/PRs ignored | Permanent fork |
| Upstream actively broken in a way that blocks Mads today | Temporary fork immediately; don't wait |
| Fix is >20 lines or architectural | Discuss with Trinity before forking |

---

## Key Rule: Keep the Diff Small

The goal is PR acceptance, not feature completeness. If Trinity's audit lists MINOR
hygiene items alongside BLOCKERs, only apply the BLOCKERs to the local-test fork.
Submit hygiene as a follow-on PR after the BLOCKER PR is accepted.

A small, focused diff is easier for the upstream maintainer to review and accept.
